Usually see one or two of these larger Grasshoppers each year it seems.

Discovered on a survey by myself, Dave Stith, and James Dillane, which turned out to be a rediscovery of plants originally spotted by Dave five years earlier or so, and spotted by someone else even earlier, in 1998.

The location is not from a GPS point taken at this location; it is estimated from my saved track that did not retain a time stamp.

The location is pretty easy to find, though.  Note the pool of water at lower right in the second pix.

Someone must have planted these here.  There was a mention of them being at Skunk Cabbage Meadow in 1998, so they have been here at least ten years.

The original URL for that report, which included a pix of them in bloom, was:

http://www.ugcs.caltech.edu/~warrior/photopre04.html

You can still retrieve that page on the internet archive:

https://archive.org/index.php

I have occasionally casually looked for these again between 2008 and 2021, when I was doing surveys for other plants here, but never saw them again, probably because:

1.  I never brought even an approximate GPS point for them.

2.  I usually couldn't remember  the exact location.

3.  I was never again early enough in the year for them to be easily seen.
Mostly hidden under a rock.

description: Dugan Ranch

Found these as a scattering of white spots on the inside of rotting red fir bark. Put them under the scope, and took a look. Working with Brian Perry we got an id here of Hyaloscypha hyalina.

Hard to tell what they are at all by eye, very small white spots.

These were a new on me, Dr. Desjardin took these are has put in the SFSU herarium for future study. These were only found up there once before, a few years ago, and now again. I had almost dismissed them as yet another ubiquitous Clitocybe albirhiza, of which there were far too many on the hill side. But these were too small and slender for that. The caps are very fibrous, and shaggy. But the key feature was the spores, they were sub-globose and distinctly ornamented, I said they look like they had a bad hair cut. Interesting little guys.

6/24/2008 – Adding a shot of the spores, at 1000x under oil. This was one of the better shots of a spore, it was hard to get the ornamention in focus. But here you can see the spore is subglobose, and warted. The warts are rather large, and seem to point away from the apiculus. Giving it a star-like appearance, or like the spore has a bad hair cut.

Funny little guys, hadn’t seen them before out in the wild. I guessed the id, and turned out to be correct. The real character of these is the stinky rancid, fish-like odor when they are mature (or something like that…).

These were found and brought to me. They were in among moss, and with the brown caps, and the lighter colored gills it was thought they might be Galerina. I put them under the scope, and not so much. They have short cheilocystidia which were pointed to subcapitate, no pleurocysitidia. Which could be Galerina, but the spores gave it away. They were non-dextrinoid, thick walled, smooth, smokey-brown in KOH with a clear germ pore. Which makes these Psilocybe. They were found near another collection of older P. montana.

7/31/2008 – Getting back to this, and adding some photos.

The first micro-shot here is of the gill edge, at 400x in Meltzer’s. Here some of the relatively short cheilocystidia can be seen, with some acute and some blunt ends. Also the spores are non-dextrinoid

The second micro-shot is of the spores from the stipe apex at 1000x in KOH. Here the spores are clearly thick-walled, smooth with blunt ends and a large germ pore.

Ave spore size : length – 8.76 +/- 0.63 (err 0.12) um, width – 5.63 +/- 0.32 (err: 0.07) – q : 1.56 +/- 0.09, on 31 spores.

As found in the mountains, with moss, and clearly Psilocybe, this makes these P. montana by the current accepted concept around here. But Guzman makes a big deal in his monograph separating species by “subellipsoid” and “rhomboid” spores. P. montana is supposed to be on the “rhomboid” branch, and these spores I’m not sure look “rhomboid”.

But also I haven’t looked at that many Psilocybe spores, so who knows.

Cute little guys, small Psathyrellas. The caps are rather shaggy in aspect, with veil tissue on the margins. Dr. Desjardin said that he hadn’t seen these before up there, and couldn’t get a species name for them.
More of the unknown Pholiota that we found so much of on the edges of snow banks in Shasta. So, it is a good year for this guy, what ever it is, now seen at more than one area.
And, another Pholiota, this one is the more common one on burnt ground. It must have been a good year of Pholiota up in the mountains.

These were id’ed by Prof. Desjardin. He looked at them under the scope, and stated they were different than the Pholiota highlandensis. Physically they were a bit different, thicked in the stipe and cap, stipes were whiter. But I’m not sure it would be easy to tell them appart.

It was a good year for these, something about the weather being just right. But anyplace there was burnt wood, there were these. The second shot shows a pile of charcoal I came across, and it was covered with the caps. So, I took a few shots of how variable this one is, the first shot is young fresh ones, and the stipes are light-tan-pallid, with a clear fibrous annulus. The second shot is of older ones, and they have darkened, with dark stipes and often no clear annulus. The third shot is of another collection where they are smaller and older. This species also has a universal veil, which isn’t always seen, but in the first two you can see the universal veil tissue on the caps.
The margins of these are free, not connected to the stipe. Under the free margins the surface is white.
Is it just me, or does this one have the longest name in the list? A full two lines long…

On bear dung. Brought in by Brian Perry. He had gone out that morning and brought back, what he reffered to as, a big basket of poo. He was pretty excited about it, relatively, I think he even wrote a little song about it. But that might have been after the Knobs Creek was passed around, I’m not sure at this point, my memory gets a little fuzzy after that…
Found by a student in the class, under mixed conifer. I had only seen these for the first time a couple days before, and here they are again. A “good” year for these perhaps?

Ok, I’ll admit it, I can’t tell the difference in the descriptions between A.
silvicola and A. abolutescens. I believe that Fred Stephens looked at this one, and said he would call it A. silvicola. So, I’ll take his word for this one (unless I’ve gone and remembered all this backwards).
Just to show how variable this annoying little fungus is, these were found only a few feet apart. One group almost black, the other almost white.

Very cool find.  It was like this, out of the water among the seaweed along the beach facing the harbor.  Usually the burrow in the mud, and this thing was definitely still alive, so I don't know if it was sick or confused or what.  Never seen one before though, and probably won't again unless I start digging in the mud (the next fronteir?).  I don't think they're usually this pink either.  Perhaps the color was the result of exposure to the sun.

Mm, contrast. I was pretty happy to re-encounter Cuthona abronia after John's many recent finds in this genus. Lisa, the common name really should be LITE-BRITE Slug. Genius.

Ah, a sacoglossan! First one I've seen in CA, I think. I'm fairly sure this is Hedgpeth's Sapsucker (Elysia hedgpethi). It's not quite the dark green color shown in Behrens & Hermosillo (2005), but the book does say yellowish brown is a possible color variant, and it certainly has the tiny blue spots. I saw this stretching on a piece of brown algae, which I think is the only way I was able to see it. About 8 mm.

I found a Flabellina with some eggs down the wall of a pool immediately in front of me, so I stuck G9 in the pool, pointed it back toward the wall (and me), and tried to aim the camera, shooting blind. After a few shots I got a mediocre one with the slug in frame. What I didn't notice until I got home that one of my "bad" shots contained this other creature, which I believe to be a nudibranch, and certainly not another F. trilineata. I suspect that this is Catriona columbiana, due to the dense, dark cerata that eventually become white at the tips. If you use your imagination, there is a hint of orange toward the head that might be part of the orange rhinophores and feeding tentacles. Behrens & Hermosillo (2005) also say they feed on the hydroid Tubularia, and this thing is definitely headed straight for a hydroid that might very well be Tubularia. The slug was at least 1 cm long, if not longer, observed at Bean Hollow State Beach, Pescadero, CA, USA. Can anyone confirm the ID or offer alternatives? I've done nothing to the image other than crop it and change the white balance to auto, because it was shot in underwater mode, which shifts colors toward the reds to compensate for red filtering at depth, and this was only in a tidepool. The sensation of finding a potentially interesting creature in a photo that you didn't intend to take is odd. Cool because it's new, frustrating because I didn't actually see it. Sort of like the flipside of seeing something awesome and then realizing your batteries just died.

As we were walking back from lunch, this guy (gal?) was just sitting on the rocks.  The only other time I've seen them was up in Seattle, birding with Minette, n8, and Minette's friend Wendy, so I was sort of shocked to see one down in Monterey in the middle of summer.
We saw a TON of Hermissendas on the first dive when we were checking out the tube anemones, giant ones, but only a couple on the second.  This one had seen better days.
Only saw a few of these on the dive.  Perhaps they prefer shallower waters?  Also on view here are some skeleton shrimp and a bunch of hydroids.
This was the second one we saw on the dive.  The coloration was slightly different.
Another totally new slug for me.  I guess these occur intertidally, but I've never spotted one.  about 3-4 cm long.
Yay, first Californian Limacia! This is Limacia cockerelli, an absolutely amazing sea slug, incredibly colorful and bizarre. This one was only about 2-3 cm long.
Pretty chunky fish, hiding among the rocks.  Perhaps this is what the fishermen up above were after.
The Warty Sea Cucumber.  These were true giants, a meter long.  Unbelievable.  When I saw huge cukes in Hawaii, I had no idea they reached similar sizes here in CA.
The California Sea Cucumber.  Pretty much unmistakable (I hope), what with it's flame orange color and anime-style spikey do.  We saw some MASSIVE specimens down there, like 30-40 cm.

There were SO many sea cukes down there. I'm afraid I can't ID this one any further down that this. The only proper key I have is in Light and Smith, and it both requires some full body characters like tube feat and deals only with intertidal creatures, and this might not qualify. On top of that, while this resembles the description of the Stiff-footed Sea Cucumber (Eupentacta quinquesemita) in The Beachcomber's Guide, there are several other species that key out along with that one in Light's. Oh well. Anyone have any great resources on sea cukes? The plume here was about 15 cm in diameter, I think.
Super camo on this guy.  Carapace around 5-7 cm in.  Unlike similar majid crabs that decorate their shells with algae, these crabs usually let encrusting animals grow there instead.
One of the pandalid shrimps, but which one?  Between 3-5 cm long, observed at a depth of ~45 ft off the Breakwater in Monterey, CA.
Good to see an old tidepool friend under the waves.  Not sure if the shrimp is commensal or just chilling.
Another D. iris, this one with slightly different coloration. You can also see some of the muck we were dealing with on this dive. Like 5 ft of vis! Not great.
This is an awesome, awesome slug, and many thanks to Brenna for introducing me to it.  Big (like, 10 cm), colorful, wacky, and they swim!
Tube anemone! They're actually in their own Order separate from most other sea anemones. Favorite snack of Dendronotus iris.
